aa(lp9
VOne night, sophomore year of college,
p10
aVjust back from Thanksgiving holiday,
p11
aVa few of my friends and I were horsing around,
p12
aVand we decided to climb atop a parked commuter train.
p13
aVIt was just sitting there, with the wires that run overhead.
p14
aVSomehow, that seemed like a great idea at the time.
p15
aVWe'd certainly done stupider things.
p16
aVI scurried up the ladder on the back,
p17
aVand when I stood up,
p18
aVthe electrical current entered my arm,
p19
aVblew down and out my feet, and that was that.
p20
aVWould you believe that watch still works?
p21
aVTakes a licking!
p22
aa(lp23
V(Laughter)
p24
aa(lp25
VMy father wears it now in solidarity.
p26
aa(lp27
VThat night began my formal relationship with death \u2014 my death \u2014
p28
aVand it also began my long run as a patient.
p29
aVIt's a good word.
p30
aVIt means one who suffers.
p31
aVSo I guess we're all patients.
p32
aa(lp33
VNow, the American health care system
p34
aVhas more than its fair share of dysfunction \u2014
p35
aVto match its brilliance, to be sure.
p36
aVI'm a physician now, a hospice and palliative medicine doc,
p37
aVso I've seen care from both sides.
p38
aVAnd believe me: almost everyone who goes into healthcare
p39
aVreally means well \u2014 I mean, truly.
p40
aVBut we who work in it are also unwitting agents
p41
aVfor a system that too often does not serve.
p42
aa(lp43
VWhy?
p44
aVWell, there's actually a pretty easy answer to that question,
p45
aVand it explains a lot:
p46
aVbecause healthcare was designed with diseases, not people, at its center.
p47
aVWhich is to say, of course, it was badly designed.
p48
aVAnd nowhere are the effects of bad design more heartbreaking
p49
aVor the opportunity for good design more compelling
p50
aVthan at the end of life,
p51
aVwhere things are so distilled and concentrated.
p52
aVThere are no do-overs.
p53
aa(lp54
VMy purpose today is to reach out across disciplines
p55
aVand invite design thinking into this big conversation.
p56
aVThat is, to bring intention and creativity
p57
aVto the experience of dying.
p58
aVWe have a monumental opportunity in front of us,
p59
aVbefore one of the few universal issues
p60
aVas individuals as well as a civil society:
p61
aVto rethink and redesign how it is we die.
p62
aa(lp63
VSo let's begin at the end.
p64
aVFor most people, the scariest thing about death isn't being dead,
p65
aVit's dying, suffering.
p66
aVIt's a key distinction.
p67
aVTo get underneath this, it can be very helpful
p68
aVto tease out suffering which is necessary as it is,
p69
aVfrom suffering we can change.
p70
aVThe former is a natural, essential part of life, part of the deal,
p71
aVand to this we are called to make space, adjust, grow.
p72
aVIt can be really good to realize forces larger than ourselves.
p73
aVThey bring proportionality,
p74
aVlike a cosmic right-sizing.
p75
aVAfter my limbs were gone,
p76
aVthat loss, for example, became fact, fixed \u2014
p77
aVnecessarily part of my life,
p78
aVand I learned that I could no more reject this fact than reject myself.
p79
aVIt took me a while, but I learned it eventually.
p80
aVNow, another great thing about necessary suffering
p81
aVis that it is the very thing
p82
aVthat unites caregiver and care receiver \u2014
p83
aVhuman beings.
p84
aVThis, we are finally realizing, is where healing happens.
p85
aVYes, compassion \u2014 literally, as we learned yesterday \u2014
p86
aVsuffering together.
p87
aa(lp88
VNow, on the systems side, on the other hand,
p89
aVso much of the suffering is unnecessary, invented.
p90
aVIt serves no good purpose.
p91
aVBut the good news is, since this brand of suffering is made up,
p92
aVwell, we can change it.
p93
aVHow we die is indeed something we can affect.
p94
aVMaking the system sensitive to this fundamental distinction
p95
aVbetween necessary and unnecessary suffering
p96
aVgives us our first of three design cues for the day.
p97
aVAfter all, our role as caregivers, as people who care,
p98
aVis to relieve suffering \u2014 not add to the pile.
p99
aa(lp100
VTrue to the tenets of palliative care,
p101
aVI function as something of a reflective advocate,
p102
aVas much as prescribing physician.
p103
aVQuick aside: palliative care \u2014 a very important field but poorly understood \u2014
p104
aVwhile it includes, it is not limited to end of life care.
p105
aVIt is not limited to hospice.
p106
aVIt's simply about comfort and living well at any stage.
p107
aVSo please know that you don't have to be dying anytime soon
p108
aVto benefit from palliative care.
