aa(lp272
VHere, this gets right at the distinction
p273
aVbetween a disease-centered and a patient- or human-centered model of care,
p274
aVand here is where caring becomes a creative, generative,
p275
aVeven playful act.
p276
aV"Play" may sound like a funny word here.
p277
aVBut it is also one of our highest forms of adaptation.
p278
aVConsider every major compulsory effort it takes to be human.
p279
aVThe need for food has birthed cuisine.
p280
aVThe need for shelter has given rise to architecture.
p281
aVThe need for cover, fashion.
p282
aVAnd for being subjected to the clock,
p283
aVwell, we invented music.
p284
aVSo, since dying is a necessary part of life,
p285
aVwhat might we create with this fact?
p286
aVBy "play" I am in no way suggesting we take a light approach to dying
p287
aVor that we mandate any particular way of dying.
p288
aVThere are mountains of sorrow that cannot move,
p289
aVand one way or another, we will all kneel there.
p290
aVRather, I am asking that we make space \u2014
p291
aVphysical, psychic room, to allow life to play itself all the way out \u2014
p292
aVso that rather than just getting out of the way,
p293
aVaging and dying can become a process of crescendo through to the end.
p294
aVWe can't solve for death.
